\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & f\left(x\right)\\
\textup{subject to} & x\in\mathcal{C},
\end{array}\tag{OPT}\label{eq:original_problem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the decision variable.
 The constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty and compact (closed and bounded), but it is not necessarily
 convex.
 The cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\mathbf{R}\cup\left\{ +\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

 is CPC.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is (i) 
\bar under
c
\bar default
onvex, (ii) 
\bar under
p
\bar default
roper, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf dom}}f=\{x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\mid f(x)<\infty\}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty, and (iii) 
\bar under
c
\bar default
losed (or lower-semicontinuous), 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 its epigraph 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf epi}}f=\left\{ (x,\xi)\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\times\mathbf{R}\mid f(x)\leq\xi\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a closed set.
 The constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be closed so that projection onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined, and it is assumed to be bounded to avoid the possibility
 of an unbounded optimal solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the following 
\series bold
heuristic based on the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 27.2"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 to solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}x_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(z_{n}\right)\\
y_{n+1} & =\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(2x_{n+1}-z_{n}\right)\\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}+y_{n+1}-x_{n+1},
\end{aligned}
\tag{NC-DRS}\label{eq:DR_splitting_orig}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 is an iteration counter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
Euclidean projection
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily convex, there can be multiple projections onto it from
 a point outside 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)=\textrm{argmin}_{y\in\mathop{{\bf dom}}f}\big(f(y)+\frac{1}{2\gamma}\|y-x\|^{2}\big)
\]

\end_inset

is the 
\series bold
proximal operator
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 We also investigate the following 
\series bold
heuristic based on ADMM
\series default
 (also known as NC-ADMM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 3.1"
key "Diamond2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) to solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}x_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(y_{n}-z_{n}\right)\\
y_{n+1} & =\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x_{n+1}+z_{n}\right)\\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}-y_{n+1}+x_{n+1},
\end{aligned}
\tag{NC-ADMM}\label{eq:ADMM_orig-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 is an iteration counter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 Note that both heuristics consist of the same subroutines, but different
 inputs are fed into them.
 So, any software package that implements one of the heuristics can be easily
 modified to implement the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is convex, then the iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n},y_{n}$
\end_inset

 in both 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 converge to an optimal solution for any initial point 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary 27.4"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boyd2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The convergence conditions for the nonconvex case, studied in this paper,
 are far more complicated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is motivated by the recent success of ADMM in solving nonconvex
 problems.
 ADMM, which is a special case of the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm
 in a convex setup, was originally designed to solve convex optimization
 problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boyd2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, since the idea of implementing this algorithm as a general purpose
 heuristics to solve nonconvex optimization problems was introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boyd2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 has been applied successfully to minimization of convex functions over
 nonconvex sets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Diamond2018,Takapoui2017a,Takapoui2017,takapoui2016simple"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and it has been implemented recently in the Python package NCVX—an extension
 of CVXPY—to formulate and solve problems of the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diamond2016cvxpy"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In these works, the nonconvex projection step of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, if computationally too costly, is replaced with a tractable 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

approximate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 projection onto the nonconvex set, 
\emph on
e.g.,
\emph default
 rounding for Boolean variables; yet it finds approximate solutions to a
 wide variety of nonconvex problems effectively.
 In spite of the empirical success, not much has been done to improve the
 theoretical understanding of such heuristics.
 Some recent progress has been made on understanding convergence of ADMM
 for specialized nonconvex setups, such as (i) minimizing a nonconvex function
 over an affine set 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang2015global"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and (ii) minimizing the sum of a smooth function with a bounded Hessian
 and a nonsmooth function with an easy to compute proximal mapping 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li2015global"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, these works are
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
newgeometry{top=0.75in, bottom=0.75in, left=0.75in, right=0.75in}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 not applicable to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, which has motivated us to investigate the convergence properties of these
 heuristics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our contributions in this paper are as follows.
 First, we characterize global minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 and show that they are related to the fixed point set of the underlying
 Douglas-Rachford operator constructed from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
 Then, we establish conditions under which 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 either converges to a point (not necessarily an optimal solution) or its
 cluster points form a nonempty compact and connected set.
 In the case where the heuristic converges to a point, we provide sufficient
 conditions for that point to be an optimal solution.
 Then, we investigate the relationship between 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 For a convex optimization problem, ADMM is the Douglas-Rachford algorithm
 splitting applied to the dual problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gabay1983"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, but their relationship is more involved in our nonconvex setup.
 Applying the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm to the convex dual of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 results in a relaxed version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, where the projection is onto the convex hull of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 We show that this relaxed algorithm finds a minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over the convex hull of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, and by restricting its projection step onto the original constraint set
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, we arrive at 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 The construction procedure also explains why, when compared with exact
 solvers, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 often achieves lower objective values in many numerical experiments performed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Diamond2018,Takapoui2017a,Takapoui2017,takapoui2016simple"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 We comment on the convergence properties of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 and compare it with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
 Our study indicates that the theoretical rationale to use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 is stronger than that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 To the best of our knowledge, we are not aware of similar results in the
 existing literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Notation and notions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the sets of real numbers and natural numbers by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathbf{R}}=\mathbf{R}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

 denotes the extended real line.
 The set of real column vectors of length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Depending on the context, 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 may be a scalar or a column vector of zeros.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The standard Euclidean norm is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\cdot\|$
\end_inset

.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot\mid\cdot\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as the inner product in the Euclidean space.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be two nonempty subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}+\mathcal{Y}=\{x+y\mid x\in\mathcal{X},y\in\mathcal{Y}\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}-\mathcal{Y}=\{x-y\mid x\in\mathcal{X},y\in\mathcal{Y}\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z+\mathcal{X}=\{z\}+\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}-z=\mathcal{X}-\{z\}$
\end_inset

.
 If one of the sets is empty, then the resultant addition or subtraction
 is an empty set, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}+\emptyset=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the
\series bold
 indicator function
\series default
 of a nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{X}}$
\end_inset

, is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{\mathcal{X}}(x)=\begin{cases}
0, & \textrm{if}\;x\in\mathcal{X}\\
\infty, & \textrm{if}\;x\notin\mathcal{X}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using indicator function, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{minimize}\;f(x)+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background on monotone operator theory
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Background-and-preliminaries"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present some definitions and preliminary results on
 monotone operator theory and relate them to our setup.
 First, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Operator-theoretic-notion"

\end_inset

, we briefly review the essential operator theoretic notions and provide
 examples that relate these concepts to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Nonexpansive,-firmly-nonexpansiv"

\end_inset

, we review nonexpansiveness and its several variants for an operator.
 These concepts are essential for characterizing (i) the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset

 and (ii) the fixed point sets of the underlying operators of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Resolvent-and-reflected"

\end_inset

, we introduce resolvent and reflected resolvent of an operator to provide
 additional characterizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Operator theoretic notions 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Operator-theoretic-notion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A
\series bold
 set-valued operator
\series default
\emph on
 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 maps each element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to a set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

; its
\emph on
 
\series bold
\emph default
domain
\series default
 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf dom}}T=\left\{ x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\mid T(x)\neq\emptyset\right\} $
\end_inset

, its 
\series bold
range
\series default
 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf ran}}T=\bigcup_{x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}}T(x)$
\end_inset

, and it is completely completely characterized by its 
\series bold
graph
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf gra}}T=\{(x,u)\mid u\in Tx\}.$
\end_inset

 Furthermore, the 
\series bold
zero set
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}T=\left\{ x\mid0\in A\left(x\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

, and the
\series bold
 fixed point set
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}T=\left\{ x\mid Tx\ni x\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $2T-I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
reflection of
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Inverse
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

, is defined through its graph: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf gra}}T^{-1}=\left\{ (u,x)\mid(x,u)\in\mathop{{\bf gra}}T\right\} $
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in T(u)\Leftrightarrow u\in T^{-1}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
addition of two operators
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2}:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}+T_{2}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T_{1}+T_{2}\right)\left(x\right)=T_{1}\left(x\right)+T_{2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 (subtraction is defined analogously), and 
\series bold
composition
\series default
 of these operators, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}T_{2},$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}T_{2}\left(x\right)=T_{1}\left(T_{2}\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

; note that order matters for composition.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty set, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathcal{X})=\bigcup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}T(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set-valued operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
monotone
\series default
 if, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,u\right),(y,v)\in\mathop{{\bf gra}}T$
\end_inset

, it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x-y\mid u-v\right\rangle \geq0$
\end_inset

.
 A monotone operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
maximally monotone
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf gra}}T$
\end_inset

 is not properly contained by the graph of any other monotone operator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, a
\series bold
 single-valued operator
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{D}\to\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a special type of set-valued operator, which maps every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in its domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to a singleton 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
projection operator
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:(Projection-operator)"

\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a
\series bold
 
\series default
Euclidean projection of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 onto the constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is single-valued.
 The set of all projections onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

, is the 
\series bold
set-valued projection operator
\series default
 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, and it is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)=\textrm{argmin}_{y\in\mathcal{C}}\|x-y\|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 are monotone operators, but not necessarily maximally monotone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 20.12"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The projection operator onto a nonempty closed convex set, however, is
 maximally monotone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 20.12, Corollary 20.27, and Proposition 4.8"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example

\series bold
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
subdifferential operator
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:Subdifferential-operator"

\end_inset

For every proper function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

, its subdifferential operator is the set-valued operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, which is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial g\left(x\right)=\left\{ u\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\mid\left(\forall y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\,g\left(y\right)\geq g\left(x\right)+\left\langle u\mid y-x\right\rangle \right\} .\label{eq:subdifferential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\partial g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
subgradient
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is subdifferentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g\left(x\right)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The subdifferential operator of a proper function is monotone, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is monotone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 20.3"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the subdifferential operator of a CPC function is maximally
 monotone, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f$
\end_inset

 is maximally monotone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 20.40"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The following result regarding the subdifferential operator plays a key
 role in characterizing global minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Convergence-analysis-for-NCDR"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\shape up
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\shape up
Fermat's rule 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 223"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\emph on
,
\shape default
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 2.3"
key "subgradBoyd"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\series bold

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:(Fermat's-rule)"

\end_inset


\series default
\shape default
 The set of all global minimizers of a proper function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\rm argmin}}g$
\end_inset

, is equal to the zero set of its subdifferential operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\textup{argmin}}g=\mathop{{\bf zer}}\partial g=\left\{ x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\mid0\in\partial g(x)\right\} .$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Take 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathop{{\rm argmin}}g$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\forall y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;g(y)\geq g(x)+\left\langle 0\mid y-x\right\rangle \Leftrightarrow\partial g(x)\ni0\Leftrightarrow x\in\mathop{{\bf zer}}\partial g.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the second line of the proof suggests that a proper function is
 always subdifferentiable at its global minimizer, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 being a subgradient there.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

While this simple characterization of optimality via the subdifferential
 holds for every nonconvex functions, it may not be particularly useful
 in practice if we cannot compute the subdifferential in an algorithmic
 manner 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 4"
key "subgradBoyd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now present a lemma regarding the subdifferential operator of the sum
 of two proper functions, which is used later in 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Convergence-analysis-for-NCDR"

\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\left(g+h\right)\left(x\right)=\partial\left(g(x)+h(x)\right)$
\end_inset

 according to our notation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
subdifferential of sum of proper functions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:subdifferential-monotone"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 be proper functions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf dom}}g\cap\mathop{{\bf dom}}h\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
(i)
\emph default
 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g+h$
\end_inset

 is proper,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
(ii)
\emph default
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g\left(x\right)+\partial h\left(x\right)\subseteq\partial(g+h)(x)$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
(iii)
\emph default
 both 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial(g+h)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g+\partial h$
\end_inset

 are monotone operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i): By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf dom}}\left(g+h\right)=\left\{ x\mid g(x)+h(x)<\infty\right\} =\mathop{{\bf dom}}g\cap\mathop{{\bf dom}}h\neq\emptyset.$
\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $g+h$
\end_inset

 is proper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii): Take 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\partial g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\partial h\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We want to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $u+v\in\partial\left(g+h\right)\left(x\right)=\partial\left(g(x)+h(x)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:subdifferential"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(y\right)\geq g\left(x\right)+\left\langle u\mid y-x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(y\right)\geq h\left(x\right)+\left\langle v\mid y-x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Adding the last two inequalities we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(g\left(y\right)+h\left(y\right)\right)\geq\left(g\left(x\right)+h\left(x\right)\right)+\left\langle u+v\mid y-x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $u+v\in\partial\left(g\left(x\right)+h\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(iii): Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:=g+h$
\end_inset

, which is proper due to (i).
 Now take 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,u),(y,v)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf gra}}\partial\phi$
\end_inset

, so we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(y\right)\geq\phi\left(x\right)+\left\langle u\mid y-x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)\geq\phi(y)+\left\langle v\mid x-y\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:subdifferential"

\end_inset

; adding these inequalities we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\geq\left\langle u\mid y-x\right\rangle +\left\langle v\mid x-y\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u-v\mid x-y\right\rangle \geq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\phi=\partial\left(g+h\right)$
\end_inset

 is a monotone operator by definition.
 Furthermore, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial h$
\end_inset

 are monotone, as the subdifferential operator of a proper function is monotone
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 20.3"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Using also the fact that sum of two monotone operators is a monotone operator
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 351"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g+\partial h$
\end_inset

 is monotone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nonexpansive and firmly nonexpansive operator
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Nonexpansive,-firmly-nonexpansiv"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{D}\to\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a single-valued operator, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
nonexpansive
\series default
\emph on
 
\emph default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert T\left(x\right)-T\left(y\right)\right\Vert \leq\|x-y\|$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
firmly nonexpansive
\series default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\|T\left(x\right)-T\left(y\right)\|^{2}+\left\Vert (I_{n}-T)(x)-(I_{n}-T)(y)\right\Vert ^{2}\leq\|x-y\|^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{D}\to\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is firmly nonexpansive on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its reflection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $2T-I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonexpansive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 4.2"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, a firmly nonexpansive operator is also nonexpansive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 59"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example

\series bold
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
proximal operator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "(proximal-operator)-The"

\end_inset

The proximal operator of a CPC function is both firmly nonexpansive and
 nonexpansive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 12.27, Example 23.3"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 is both firmly nonexpansive and nonexpansive.
 Furthermore, its reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $2\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is nonexpansive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 4.2"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example

\series bold
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
projection operator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "expansiveness_projection_operator"

\end_inset

We remind the reader that, a set is called 
\series bold
proximinal
\series default
 if every point has at least one projection onto it, whereas it is called
 a 
\series bold
Chebyshev
\series default
 set if every point has exactly one projection onto it.
 A nonempty subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is Chebyshev if and only if it is closed and convex 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Remark 3.15"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and the projection operator onto such a set is single-valued and firmly
 nonexpansive on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 4.8"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, for the constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, which is possibly nonconvex, the projection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is not, in general, nonexpansive, hence not firmly nonexpansive.
 For example, consider the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

; the projections of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.6$
\end_inset

 onto this set are 0 and 1, respectively, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|0.6-0.4|=0.2<1$
\end_inset

, which violates the definition of nonexpansiveness.
 In such a case, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

 is also not nonexpansive, because an operator is firmly nonexpansive if
 and only if its reflection operator is nonexpansive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 4.2"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We now introduce the following definitions to (i) characterize an operator
 that is not necessarily nonexpansive (
\emph on
e.g.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

) and (ii) measure the deviation of such an operator from being nonexpansive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Expansiveness of an operator
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Expansiveness-of-an-op"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{D}\to\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a single-valued operator.
 The
\series bold
 expansiveness
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

, is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}=\begin{cases}
\|T(x)-T(y)\|-\|x-y\|,\\
\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\textrm{if }\|x-y\|<\|T(x)-T(y)\|\\
0,\qquad\qquad\qquad\quad{\rm else}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where it is nonnegative and symmetric, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}=\varepsilon_{yx}^{(T)}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|T(x)-T(y)\|\leq\|x-y\|+\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}.\label{eq:N_x_y-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Next, we define the 
\series bold
squared expansiveness bias 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

, as:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}=\begin{cases}
\sqrt{\|T(x)-T(y)\|^{2}-\|x-y\|^{2}}, & \textrm{if }\|x-y\|<\|T(x)-T(y)\|\\
0, & \textrm{else.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\size default
Furthermore, define, 
\series bold
squared expansiveness
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}=\begin{cases}
\sqrt{\|T(x)-T(y)\|^{2}-\|x-y\|^{2}},\\
\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\textrm{if }\|x-y\|<\|T(x)-T(y)\|\\
0,\qquad\qquad\qquad\quad{\rm else}.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

 can be defined through 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon{}_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}=\sqrt{\varepsilon{}_{xy}^{(T)}}\sqrt{\|T(x)-T(y)\|+\|x-y\|}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\|T(x)-T(y)\|^{2}\leq\|x-y\|^{2}+\big(\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}\big)^{2}.\label{eq:M_x_y-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
further characterization of nonexpansive operators
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "(further-characterization-of"

\end_inset

An operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is nonexpansive on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}=\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}=0$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is not nonexpansive if and only if there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in its domain such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

 is positive.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}^{(T)}$
\end_inset

 measure the deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 from being a nonexpansive operator at 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resolvent and reflected resolvent of an operator
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Resolvent-and-reflected"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a set-valued operator and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
resolvent
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma T}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma T}=(I_{n}+\gamma T)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and its 
\series bold
reflected resolvent,
\series default
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\gamma T}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\gamma T}=2J_{\gamma T}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The proximal operator of a function is intimately connected to the resolvent
 of that function's subdifferential operator as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
resolvent characterization of proximal operator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 be proper, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma\partial g}$
\end_inset

 are set-valued, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma g}(x)\subseteq J_{\gamma\partial g}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is CPC, then both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma\partial g}$
\end_inset

 are single-valued, firmly nonexpansive and continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma g}(x)=J_{\gamma\partial g}(x)$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
When 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is proper, the claim follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 10.2"
key "Rockafellar2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 When, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is CPC, the claim follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 12.27"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pages 59-60"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 23.3"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following corollary applies Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

 to the constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary

\emph on
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\emph off
resolvent characterization of projection
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Proximal-operator-of"

\end_inset


\emph default
 For the constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}\left(x\right)=\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{C}}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For a convex set, all these operators are single-valued, firmly nonexpansive,
 and equal to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Follows directly from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

 and the definitions of the proximal operator and the projection operator.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We end this section by recording a result on how to represent of zeros of
 two monotone operators by the fixed points of their resolvents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 25.1 (ii)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\series bold
\emph on
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Zeros-of"

\end_inset

 (zeros of two monotone operators' sum)
\series default
\emph default
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2}:\mathbf{R}^{n}\rightrightarrows\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are two monotone operators with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(T_{1}+T_{2}\right)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(T_{1}+T_{2}\right)=J_{\gamma T_{1}}\left(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\left(R_{\gamma T_{2}}R_{\gamma T_{1}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

