\begin_layout Subsection
Supporting lemmas on sequences
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Supporting-lemmas-on"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this subsection, we present some supporting lemmas on sequences to be
 used later; the first three results concern convergence of a sequence of
 scalars, and the fourth result is about convergence of a sequence of vectors
 in a compact set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we briefly review the definitions and basic properties of limit inferior
 and limit superior of a sequence.

\series bold
 Limit inferior
\series default
 and 
\series bold
limit superior
\series default
 of a scalar sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\alpha_{n} & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\big(\inf_{m\geq n}\alpha_{m}\big),\textrm{and}\\
\underset{n\to\infty}{\overline{\lim}}\alpha_{n} & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\big(\sup_{m\geq n}\alpha_{m}\big),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

respectively, where they can be extended real-valued.
 For a bounded sequence, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 exist, and they are finite.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}\leq\overline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence converges if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}=\overline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}=\lim_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}\in\mathbf{R}.$
\end_inset

 Furthermore, limit inferior satisfies 
\series bold
superadditivity
\series default
, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 for every two sequences of real numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}},\left(\beta_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\left(\alpha_{n}+\beta_{n}\right)\geq\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}+\underline{\lim}_{n\to\infty}\beta_{n}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
limit inferior of a nonnegative scalar sequence
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:(a-lemma-on"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of nonnegative scalars such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n\in\mathbf{N}}\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n\in\mathbf{N}}\alpha_{n}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above, there exists a nonnegative real number 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\sum_{n\in\mathbf{N}}\alpha_{n}\leq M$
\end_inset

.
 Define the sequence of partial sums 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a bounded sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,M]$
\end_inset

, its limit inferior, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\beta_{n}$
\end_inset

, is finite.
 But, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L & =\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\beta_{n}\\
 & =\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\big(\beta_{n-1}+\alpha_{n}\big)\\
 & \overset{a)}{\geq}\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\beta_{n-1}+\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\alpha_{n}\\
 & \overset{b)}{=}L+\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\alpha_{n},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses the superadditivity property of limit inferior, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\beta_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of nonnegative terms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Combining the last two statements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\emph off
convergence of a nonnegative scalar sequence
\emph default
 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 44, Lemma 2"
key "Polyak1987"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Polyak Lemma"

\end_inset


\emph default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}},\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 be sequences of nonnegative scalars such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n+1}\leq(1+\alpha_{n})u_{n}+\beta_{n},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n\in\mathbf{N}}\alpha_{n}<\infty,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n\in\mathbf{N}}\beta_{n}<\infty.$
\end_inset

 Then, there is a nonnegative scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
limit inferior of addition of two sequences 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 2.3"
key "bworld"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:-Let-df"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\beta_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 be two bounded scalar sequences.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\alpha_{n}=\alpha$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\left(\alpha_{n}+\beta_{n}\right)=\alpha+\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\beta_{n}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we record a result about convergence of a sequence of vectors in a compact
 set.
 We remind the reader that, a set is 
\series bold
connected
\series default
 if it is not the union of two disjoint nonempty closed sets.
 A compact and connected set is called a 
\series bold
continuum
\series default
.
 Moreover, a set is called a 
\series bold
nontrivial continuum
\series default
, if it is a continuum, and it does not reduce to 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 or a singleton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Combettes1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
cluster point
\series default
 of a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 if the sequence has a subsequence that converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\emph off
convergence of a sequence of vectors in a compact set
\emph default
 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 4.2"
key "Combettes1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Combettes_Proof"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of vectors in a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x_{n+1}-x_{n}\|$
\end_inset

 converges to zero.
 Then, either 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 converges to a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, or its set of cluster points is a nontrivial continuum in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nonconvex Douglas-Rachford, Cayley and Peaceman-Rachford operators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Nonconvex-Douglas-Rachford"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To facilitate our convergence analysis, we define the following operators
 for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
nonconvex Douglas-Rachford operator
\series default
 with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{T}=\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{\mathcal{C}}}\left(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}\right)+I_{n}-\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}.\label{eq:NC-DRS-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
nonconvex Cayley operator
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 (also known as the reflection operator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

) with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{R}=2\tilde{T}-I_{n}.\label{eq:NC-Cayley-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
nonconvex Peaceman-Rachford operator
\series default
 with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{S}=(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n})(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}).\label{eq:NC-PR-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
nonconvex Peaceman-Rachford operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 is not nonexpansive
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tilde_S_nonexpansive"

\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 is a composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}$
\end_inset

, where the latter is nonexpansive (see Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(proximal-operator)-The"

\end_inset

), but the former is not nonexpansive in general (see Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "expansiveness_projection_operator"

\end_inset

).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 is not a nonexpansive operator in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These operators allow us to write 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 in the following compact form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z_{n+1}=\tilde{T}z_{n} & =\frac{1}{2}\tilde{R}z_{n}+\frac{1}{2}z_{n}.\tag{Compact-NC-DRS}\label{eq:convenient-form-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following lemma will be used later to characterize global minimizers
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
characterization of nonconvex Peaceman-Rachford operator
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tilde_S_in_R_R"

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 be the nonconvex Peaceman-Rachford operator with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NC-PR-operator"

\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}\left(x\right)\subseteq R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
As 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is CPC, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{\gamma\partial f}=2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n},\label{eq:asgard}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

 and the definition of the reflected resolvent in 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Resolvent-and-reflected"

\end_inset

.
 Now for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\big(2\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}\big)\left(x\right) & =2\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)-x\nonumber \\
 & \overset{a)}{\subseteq}2\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)-x\nonumber \\
 & \overset{b)}{\subseteq}2J_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}(x)-x\nonumber \\
 & =\big(2J_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}-I_{n}\big)x\nonumber \\
 & \overset{c)}{=}R_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}\left(x\right),\label{eq:midgard}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exa:(Projection-operator)"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 follows from Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Proximal-operator-of"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 follows from the definition of reflected resolvent in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Resolvent-and-reflected"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{S}\left(x\right) & =\big(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}\big)\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}\big)\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{a)}{=}\big(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}\big)R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{b)}{\subseteq}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:asgard"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:midgard"

\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 be the operators with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NC-DRS-operator"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NC-Cayley-operator"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NC-PR-operator"

\end_inset

, respectively.
 Then, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition

\emph on
(i)
\emph default
 the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 are equal, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}\left(x\right)=\tilde{S}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition

\emph on
(ii)
\emph default
 the fixed point sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 are equal, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i): For every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{T}\left(x\right) & =\big(\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}\big)+I_{n}-\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big)\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}\big)\left(x\right)+x-\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\big)+x-\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right).\label{eq:obs_douglas_rachford}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Furthermore, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{R}\left(x\right) & =\big(2\tilde{T}-I_{n}\big)\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
 & =2\tilde{T}\left(x\right)-x\nonumber \\
 & \overset{a)}{=}2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\right)+2x-2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\nonumber \\
 & =2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\right)+x-2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right),\label{eq:obs_douglas_rachford_2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:obs_douglas_rachford"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{S}\left(x\right) & =\big(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}\big)\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n}\big)\left(x\right)\\
 & =\big(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n}\big)\underbrace{\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\big)}_{=y\textrm{ (let)}}\\
 & =2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\left(y\right)-y\\
 & =2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}\big(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)-x\big)-2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)+x\\
 & \overset{a)}{=}\tilde{R}x,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:obs_douglas_rachford_2"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii): In (i), 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}=\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

 implying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}\Leftrightarrow\tilde{T}\left(x\right)=x\Leftrightarrow2\tilde{T}\left(x\right)=2x\Leftrightarrow2\tilde{T}\left(x\right)-x=x\Leftrightarrow\left(2\tilde{T}-I_{n}\right)\left(x\right)=x\Leftrightarrow x=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}.$
\end_inset

 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
nonconvex Cayley operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is not nonexpansive
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Cayley_is_not_nonexpansive"

\end_inset

 From Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tilde_S_nonexpansive"

\end_inset

 and Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is not a nonexpansive operator in general.
 This plays an important role in our convergence analysis; in particular,
 the sufficient conditions for convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 are dictated by the expansiveness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 over the iterates of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Characterization of global minimizers
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Characterization-of-global"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 are characterized via the nonconvex Douglas-Rachford operator as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\emph off
global minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:minimizer_charecterization"

\end_inset


\emph default
 For 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 be the nonconvex Douglas-Rachford operator with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NC-DRS-operator"

\end_inset

.
 Then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
(i)
\emph default
 sum of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is proper, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f\left(x\right)+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)$
\end_inset

 are monotone operators, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f})\big)$
\end_inset


\emph default
, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
(iii)
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 , then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}\big)\subseteq\mathop{{\rm argmin}}\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i): The indicator function of a closed set is closed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 1.25"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and the indicator function of a nonempty set is proper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pages 6-7"
key "Rockafellar2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is closed and proper.
 Also, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf dom}}f\cap\mathop{{\bf dom}}\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, otherwise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 is infeasible.
 So, using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:subdifferential-monotone"

\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is proper, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f\left(x\right)+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
, and both 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)$
\end_inset

 are monotone operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii): This proof is based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 25.1 (ii)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign}
 & x\in\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & (\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n})\;x-y\in\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}(x)\textrm{ and }y-x\in\gamma\partial f(x)\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & \left(\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;2x-y\in(I_{n}+\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}})(x)\textrm{ and }\nonumber \\
 & \mbox{\qquad\qquad\quad}y\in(I_{n}+\gamma\partial f)(x)\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & \left(\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;\underbrace{(I_{n}+\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}})^{-1}}_{=J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}}(2x-y)\ni x\textrm{ and }\nonumber \\
 & \mbox{\qquad\qquad\quad}\underbrace{(I_{n}+\gamma\partial f)^{-1}}_{=J_{\gamma\partial f}}(y)\ni x\nonumber \\
\overset{a)}{\Leftrightarrow} & \left(\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;x\in J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}(2x-y)\textrm{ and }x=J_{\gamma\partial f}(y),\nonumber \\
\overset{b)}{\Leftrightarrow} & \left(\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;x\in J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\textrm{ and }x=J_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\label{eq:shapiro}
\end{flalign}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses the facts that 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma\partial f}$
\end_inset

 is a single-valued operator (from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}$
\end_inset

 is a set-valued operator (from Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Proximal-operator-of"

\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 uses the observation that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=J_{\gamma\partial f}(y)$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=J_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\Leftrightarrow2x-y=\big(2J_{\gamma\partial f}-I_{n}\big)y=R_{\gamma\partial f}(y).
\]

\end_inset

Also, using the last expression, we can write the first term of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:shapiro"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\ni x\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & 2J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)-y\ni2x-y=R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & y\in2J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)-R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\nonumber \\
 & \;=\big(2J_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}-I_{n}\big)\big(R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\big)\nonumber \\
 & \;=R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}(y)\nonumber \\
\Leftrightarrow & y\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\big(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big).\label{eq:harris}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:shapiro"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:harris"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\gamma\partial f}=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset

 (from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

) we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & x\in\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\\
\Leftrightarrow & \left(\exists y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}\right)\;y\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\big(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big)\textrm{ and }x=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(y)\\
\Leftrightarrow & x\in\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f})\big).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f})\big).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(iii): We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & x\in\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\\
\Leftrightarrow & 0\in\partial f\left(x\right)+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\overset{a)}{\subseteq}\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\left(x\right)\\
\Rightarrow & x\in\mathop{{\bf zer}}\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial f\left(x\right)+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\left(x\right)\subseteq\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 proven in (i).
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\subseteq\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Combining the last statement with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\right)=\mathop{{\rm argmin}}\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)$
\end_inset

 (from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:(Fermat's-rule)"

\end_inset

) and (ii), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\nonumber \\
= & \mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\Big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\big(R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big)\Big)\\
\subseteq & \mathop{{\rm argmin}}\big(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big).\label{eq:nifelhaim}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Recall from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset

 is a single-valued operator.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}\big) & =\big\{\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\mid x=\tilde{S}\left(x\right)\big\}\\
 & =\big\{\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\mid x=\tilde{S}\left(x\right)\subseteq R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)\big\}\\
 & \subseteq\big\{\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\mid x\in R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)\big\}\\
 & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}\big) & =\bigcup_{x\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{x:x=\tilde{S}(x)}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{a)}{\subseteq}\bigcup_{x:x\in R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{x:x\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(x\right)\\
 & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}\left(x\right)\subseteq R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tilde_S_in_R_R"

\end_inset

).
 But, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{S}\big) & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}\big)\\
 & \subseteq\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Combining the last equation with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:nifelhaim"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}\big) & \subseteq\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\big(\mathop{{\bf fix}}R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}\big)\\
 & \subseteq\mathop{{\rm argmin}}\big(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Nonemptyness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 A necessary condition for nonmptiness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 is nonemptyness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)$
\end_inset

.
 This necessary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is stronger than the existence of a minimizer, because, even in a convex
 setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\neq\mathop{{\bf zer}}\left(\partial\left(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, in general 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Remark 16.7"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf zer}}\big(\partial f+\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\big)\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for the rest of our development, as this seems to be a standard assumption
 even in convex optimization literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Davis2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Main convergence result
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Main-convergence-result"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We remind the reader that the nonconvex Cayley operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is not nonexpansive in general (Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Cayley_is_not_nonexpansive"

\end_inset

).
 To characterize the deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 from being a nonexpansive operator, recalling 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Nonexpansive,-firmly-nonexpansiv"

\end_inset

, we use expansiveness and squared expansiveness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 at each 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

, respectively; here we have dropped the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{R})$
\end_inset

 to reduce notational burden.
 So, from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:N_x_y-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:M_x_y-1"

\end_inset

, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\|\tilde{R}(x)-\tilde{R}(y)\| & \leq\|x-y\|+\varepsilon_{xy},\textrm{and}\label{eq:N_x_y}\\
\|\tilde{R}(x)-\tilde{R}(y)\|^{2} & \leq\|x-y\|^{2}+\sigma_{xy}^{2}.\label{eq:M_x_y}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, the closed ball with center 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and finite radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x;r)$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x;r)=\{y\mid\|x-y\|\leq r\}$
\end_inset

; a closed ball in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with finite radius is compact 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 2.4"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Now we present our main convergence result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
main convergence result
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset

 For 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 be the sequence of vectors generated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
 Suppose that the following conditions are satisfied for the chosen initial
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\series bold
Condition 1.

\series default
 There exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\series bold
Condition 2.
\series default
\shape italic
The sum
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\varepsilon_{z_{n}z_{n+1}}$
\end_inset

 is bounded above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $r:=\sqrt{\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, one of the following holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
(i)
\emph default
 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 converges to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}\in B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, suppose also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(z^{\star}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an optimal solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, and the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(z^{\star})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\emph on
(ii)
\emph default
 the set of cluster points of 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 forms a nontrivial continuum in 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Step 1.

\series default
 First, we show that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 stays in the compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\|z_{n+1}-z\|^{2} & \overset{a)}{=}\|z_{n}+\frac{1}{2}\big(\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\big)-z\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & =\|\frac{1}{2}\big(z_{n}-z\big)+\frac{1}{2}\big(\tilde{R}z_{n}-z\big)\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \overset{b)}{=}\frac{1}{2}\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\frac{1}{4}\|(z_{n}-z)-(\tilde{R}z_{n}-z)\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \overset{c)}{=}\frac{1}{2}\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\frac{1}{4}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \overset{d)}{\leq}\frac{1}{2}\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}-\frac{1}{4}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}\label{eq:inequality_1-1-1}\\
 & \leq\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}-\frac{1}{4}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \overset{e)}{\leq}\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2},\label{eq:aha_ki_anondo}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convenient-form-1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 uses the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\alpha x+(1-\alpha)y\|^{2}=\alpha\|x\|^{2}+(1-\alpha)\|y\|^{2}-\alpha(1-\alpha)\|x-y\|^{2}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary 2.14"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 (from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

(ii)), 
\begin_inset Formula $d)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:M_x_y"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e)$
\end_inset

 is obtained by removing the nonpositive term 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{4}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:aha_ki_anondo"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\|z_{n}-z\|^{2} & \leq\|z_{n-1}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n-1}z}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \leq\|z_{n-2}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n-2}z}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n-1}z}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \leq\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\sigma_{z_{i}z}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \leq\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}\sigma_{z_{i}z}^{2},\label{eq:tyrs_temple}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the final term is bounded due to condition 1, hence the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 stays in the compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Step 2.
 
\series default
Next, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=0$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:inequality_1-1-1"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{4}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|^{2} & \leq\big(\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}-\|z_{n+1}-z\|^{2}\big)+\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}\\
\Rightarrow\frac{1}{4}\sum_{n=0}^{m}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|^{2} & \leq\sum_{n=0}^{m}\big(\|z_{n}-z\|^{2}-\|z_{n+1}-z\|^{2}\big)\\
 & \quad+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=0}^{m}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}\\
 & \overset{a)}{=}\big(\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}-\|z_{m+1}-z\|^{2}\big)\\
 & \quad+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=0}^{m}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}\\
 & \overset{b)}{\leq}\|z_{0}-z\|^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=0}^{m}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses the telescopic sum, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 is obtained by removing the negative term 
\begin_inset Formula $\|z_{m+1}-z\|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $m\to\infty$
\end_inset

, the right hand side of the last inequality is bounded due to condition
 1, thus using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:(a-lemma-on"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Step 3.
 
\series default
We show that sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 either converges to a point or its set of cluster points forms a nontrivial
 continuum.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|\tilde{R}z_{n+1}-z_{n+1}\| & \overset{a)}{=}\|\tilde{R}z_{n+1}-\frac{1}{2}z_{n}-\frac{1}{2}\tilde{R}z_{n}\|\\
 & =\|\big(\tilde{R}z_{n+1}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\big)+\frac{1}{2}\big(\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\big)\|\\
 & \overset{b)}{\leq}\|\tilde{R}z_{n+1}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|+\frac{1}{2}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|\\
 & \overset{c)}{\leq}\|z_{n+1}-z_{n}\|+\varepsilon_{z_{n}z_{n+1}}+\frac{1}{2}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|\\
 & \overset{d)}{\leq}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|+\varepsilon_{z_{n}z_{n+1}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convenient-form-1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 uses triangular inequality, 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:N_x_y"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\|z_{n+1}-z_{n}\|=\frac{1}{2}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|$
\end_inset

 that follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convenient-form-1"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\varepsilon_{z_{n}z_{n+1}}<+\infty$
\end_inset

 due to condition 2, thus using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Polyak Lemma"

\end_inset

, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 converges to a nonnegative number.
 Using also the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=0$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=\underset{n\to\infty}{\underline{\lim}}\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=0.$
\end_inset

 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|=2\|z_{n+1}-z_{n}\|$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convenient-form-1"

\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\|z_{n+1}-z_{n}\|=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have established that, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 stays in a compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

 and satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\|z_{n+1}-z_{n}\|=0$
\end_inset

.
 So, due to Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Combettes_Proof"

\end_inset

, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 either converges to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}\in B(z;r)$
\end_inset

 or the set of cluster points of 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 forms a nontrivial continuum in 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.

\emph on
 This proves the first part of claim 
\emph default
(i)
\emph on
 and claim 
\emph default
(ii)
\emph on
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Step 4.
 
\series default
Now we prove the second part of claim (i).
 Under the additional condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\to0,z_{n}\to z^{\star}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(z^{\star}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an optimal solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\to\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(z^{\star}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\|z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\|^{2} & \overset{a)}{=}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\|^{2}-\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-2\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =\|\big(z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\big)+\big(\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\big)\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}-2\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}+\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\|^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad+2\langle z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\mid\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & \quad-\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}-2\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & \overset{b)}{\leq}\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}+\cancel{\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}}+\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}\nonumber \\
 & \quad+2\langle z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\mid\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle-\cancel{\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}}\nonumber \\
 & \quad-2\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\|^{2}+2\langle z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\mid\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & \quad-2\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle+\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2},\label{eq:feedback}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where, 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 uses the identity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\|z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\|^{2} & =\|(z_{n}-z^{\star})+(z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star})\|^{2}\\
 & =\|z_{n}-z^{\star}\|^{2}+\|z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\|^{2}\\
 & \quad+2\left\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\right\rangle ,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:M_x_y"

\end_inset

.
 We now compute the limit (or the limit inferior) for each of the terms
 on the right-hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:feedback"

\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}\to z^{\star}$
\end_inset

, subtracting them we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}z_{n}\to z^{\star}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\to z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}.$
\end_inset

 Combining the last statement with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\to0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle z_{n}-\tilde{R}z_{n}\mid\tilde{R}z_{n}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}-z^{\star}\to0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle z_{n}-z^{\star}\mid z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}\rangle\to0.$
\end_inset

 Additionally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 So, using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:-Let-df"

\end_inset

, limit inferior of the right hand side 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:feedback"

\end_inset

 goes to zero.
 Hence, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}-\tilde{R}z^{\star}=0,$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

.
 But, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{R}=\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

(ii).
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

.
 We now recall from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:singtonness"

\end_inset

 that 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is continuous everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 So, using the definition of continuity, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}\to z^{\star}\in\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(z_{n})\to\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(z^{\star})\in\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T})$
\end_inset

.
 But, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}(\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T})\subseteq\mathop{{\rm argmin}}(f+\delta_{\mathcal{C}})$
\end_inset

 from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:minimizer_charecterization"

\end_inset

(iii).
 
\emph on
Thus we have arrived at the second part of claim 
\emph default
(i)
\emph on
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Notes on Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Notes-on-NC-DRS_conv"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We make the following notes on Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet\,$
\end_inset


\series bold
Nonemptiness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}.$
\end_inset


\series default
 Note that Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset

 assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf fix}}\tilde{T}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
 This is a standard assumption in monotone operator theory even in a convex
 setup 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 5.2"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
, , as otherwise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 will not converge to anything.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet\,$
\end_inset


\series bold
Relation to a convex setup.
 
\series default
In our convergence analysis, the constraint set is nonempty and compact,
 but not necessarily convex.
 However, our convergence analysis is also applicable to a convex setup.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 be convex.
 Then, both 
\begin_inset Formula $(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I_{n})$
\end_inset

 are nonexpansive operators, hence, their composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}=(2\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}-I)(2\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}-I)$
\end_inset

 is a nonexpansive operator.
 In such a convex setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is a nonexpansive operator, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}=\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(Relationship-between-the"

\end_inset

 (where the relationship is established irrespective of convexity).
 Then, recalling Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(further-characterization-of"

\end_inset

, expansiveness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is zero everywhere, 
\emph on
i.e.,
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{xy}=\varepsilon_{xy}=0$
\end_inset

 at every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 As a result, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a monotonically nonincreasing sequence that is bounded below, which
 guarantees convergence to a point for any initial point 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 48"
key "Polyak1987"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Also, conditions 1, 2, and the additional condition in the second part
 of claim (i) are automatically satisfied.
 This ensures that the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 converges to is an optimal solution for any initial point.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 This guarantees the convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 to an optimal solution for any initial point.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet\,$
\end_inset


\series bold
Comments on the conditions.

\series default
 Once we move from a convex setup to a nonconvex setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 is not nonexpansive anymore (recall Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Cayley_is_not_nonexpansive"

\end_inset

).
 Roughly speaking, convergence in such a case requires that the total expansiven
ess of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 stays bounded for the iterates.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\varepsilon_{z_{n}z_{n+1}}$
\end_inset

 need to be bounded, where they represent the total deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 from being a nonexpansive operator over the sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(z_{n},z\right)\right\} _{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(z_{n},z_{n+1}\right)\right\} _{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Furthermore, in a nonconvex setup, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\|\tilde{R}z_{n}-z_{n}\|)_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 is bounded, but it is not necessarily monotonically nonincreasing; this
 is why the cluster points of 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 may form a nontrivial continuum in 
\begin_inset Formula $B(z;r)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose now that 
\begin_inset Formula $(z_{n})_{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

 converges to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Whether 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is related to an optimal solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 would depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If it is zero, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f}\left(z^{\star}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an optimal solution, and the iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 converges to this optimal solution.
 Roughly speaking, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{\underline{\mathrm{lim}}}_{n\to\infty}\sigma_{z_{n}z^{\star}}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 means that over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(z_{n},z^{\star}\right)\right\} _{n\in\mathbf{N}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 acts as a nonexpansive operator in the lower limit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Construction and convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we discuss how 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 can be constructed from the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm and comment
 on how the construction influences the convergence properties of the former.
 First, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Preliminaries_NC_ADMM"

\end_inset

 we present some preliminary results to be used later.
 Then, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:NC-ADMM-from-Douglas-Rachford"

\end_inset

 we describe how 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 is constructed from the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm.
 Finally, in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Convergence-properties-of-NC-ADMM"

\end_inset

 we comment on convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, and we compare it with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Preliminaries
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Preliminaries_NC_ADMM"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we describe the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm for minimizing
 sum of two CPC functions; we will use it in the first step of constructing
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 Then, we review the necessary background on conjugate and biconjugate functions
, and we present two lemmas to be referenced in the second step of constructing
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm for minimizing sum of two CPC functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the convex optimization problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & g\left(x\right)+h(x),\end{array}\label{eq:cvx-opt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where both 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 are CPC functions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the optimization variable.
 The Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm for this problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma h}\left(z_{n}\right)\nonumber \\
y_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma g}\left(2x_{n+1}-z_{n}\right)\tag{Convex-DRS}\label{eq:classic_DRS}\\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}+y_{n+1}-x_{n+1},\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the iteration counter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a positive parameter.
 In this convex setup, both 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 converge to an optimal solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cvx-opt"

\end_inset

 for any initial point 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary 27.4"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conjugate and biconjugate of a function
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Conjugate-and-biconjugate"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\left\{ -\infty\right\} \cup\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
conjugate
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\star}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\star}\left(y\right)=\sup_{x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}}\left(\left\langle x\mid y\right\rangle -g\left(x\right)\right),$
\end_inset

 which is closed and convex irrespective of the convexity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 13.11"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Also, the conjugate of a CPC function is CPC 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 4.3, Theorem 4.5"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the 
\series bold
biconjugate
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\star\star}$
\end_inset

, is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\star\star}\left(y\right)=\sup_{x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}}\left(\left\langle x\mid y\right\rangle -g^{\star}\left(x\right)\right).$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The biconjugate of any function is always a lower bound on the original
 function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Lemma 4.7"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Additionally, if the function is CPC, then its biconjugate is equal to
 the function itself 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Lemma 4.8"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, the relationship between the proximal operator of a CPC function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with the proximal operator of its conjugate is given by 
\series bold
Moreau's decomposition
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{f}\left(x\right)+\mathbf{prox}_{f^{\star}}\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreau's decomposition does not hold for a nonconvex function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we present the following lemmas about conjugate functions in the context
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
 Here we use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\vee},$
\end_inset

 which denotes the reversal of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and it is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\vee}\left(x\right)=g\left(-x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
proximal operator of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star\vee}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prox_gamma_f_star_vee"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbf{R}^{n}\to\overline{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 be the cost function in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
 Then, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f^{\star\vee}}\left(x\right)=x+\gamma\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\left(-\gamma^{-1}x\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is CPC.
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 and for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f^{\star\vee}}\left(x\right) & \overset{a)}{=}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\left(f^{\vee}\right)^{\star}}\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{b)}{=}x-\gamma\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f^{\vee}}\left(\gamma^{-1}x\right)\\
 & \overset{c)}{=}x+\gamma\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\left(-\gamma^{-1}x\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star\vee}=f^{\vee\star}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 13.20(v)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 23.29(viii)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\vee}$
\end_inset

 is CPC, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 directly follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 23.29(v)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following Lemma 
\series bold
convex hull
\series default
 of a nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, which is the smallest convex set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathop{{\bf conv}}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\emph off
conjugate and biconjugate of indicator function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "biconjugate-of-indicator-of-C"

\end_inset


\emph default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 be the constraint set in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
(i)
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}=\delta_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma

\emph on
(ii)
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}}\left(x\right)=x-\gamma\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(\gamma^{-1}x\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i): From 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 4.2, Example 4.9"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}=\delta_{\overline{\mathop{{\bf conv}}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

.
 The constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is compact, hence its convex hull 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is also compact, hence closed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary 2.30"
key "Rockafellar2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathop{{\bf conv}}}\mathcal{C}=\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, and we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}=\delta_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii): As the constraint set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty and compact, its indicator function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is closed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Example 1.25"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and proper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 7"
key "Rockafellar2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, its conjugate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}$
\end_inset

, which is called the 
\series bold
support function
\series default
 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, is CPC (closed and convex due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 13.11"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, proper because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is bounded).
 As the conjugate of a CPC function is CPC 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 4.3, Theorem 4.5"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}$
\end_inset

 is CPC.
 Using Moreau's decomposition for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}}\left(x\right) & =x-\mathbf{prox}_{\left(\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}\right)^{\star}}\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{a)}{=}x-\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}\big(\gamma^{-1}(\cdot)\big)}\left(x\right)\\
 & \overset{b)}{=}x-\gamma\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}}\left(\gamma^{-1}x\right)\\
 & \overset{c)}{=}x-\gamma\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(\gamma^{-1}x\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 13.20(i)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 23.29(iii)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 follows from combining 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}=\delta_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 in (i) and Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Proximal-operator-of"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constructing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 from Douglas-Rachford splitting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:NC-ADMM-from-Douglas-Rachford"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subsection is organized as follows.
 First, by applying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:classic_DRS"

\end_inset

 to the convex dual of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 we construct a relaxed version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, where the projection is onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we show that the relaxed version 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, we discuss construction of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 from the relaxed variant by restricting the latter's projection step onto
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we comment on the convergence properties of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 and relate it to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constructing dual of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using indicator function, we write 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & f\left(x\right)+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}\left(y\right)\\
\textup{subject to} & x-y=0,
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are the optimization variables.
 Denote the optimal value of the problem above by 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 The dual of the reformulated problem, which is a convex optimization problem
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "\\S 5.1.6"
key "boyd2004convex"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{maximize} & -f^{\star\vee}\left(\nu\right)-\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}\left(\nu\right),\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the optimization variable.
 Denote the optimal value of the dual problem by 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to weak duality, we have, 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\star}\leq p^{\star}$
\end_inset

, and, as the primal problem is nonconvex, the duality gap 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\star}-d^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is strict in general.
 For convenience, we write the dual problem in minimization form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & f^{\star\vee}\left(\nu\right)+\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}\left(\nu\right),\end{array}\tag{Dual-OPT}\label{eq:dual-opt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $-d^{\star}$
\end_inset

 and same set of optimal solutions as the dual problem.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is CPC, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star\vee}$
\end_inset

 is also CPC (follows from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Conjugate-and-biconjugate"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 8.20"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "biconjugate-of-indicator-of-C"

\end_inset

(ii), 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is also CPC.
 Thus we can apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:classic_DRS"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Applying Douglas-Rachford splitting to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By setting 
\begin_inset Formula $g:=f^{\star\vee}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h:=\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cvx-opt"

\end_inset

, we have the following Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm for the dual
 problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\zeta_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star}}\left(\psi_{n}\right)\nonumber \\
\xi_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma f^{\star\vee}}\left(2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n}\right)\tag{Dual-DRS}\label{eq:dual-DRS}\\
\psi_{n+1} & =\psi_{n}+\xi_{n+1}-\zeta_{n+1}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "biconjugate-of-indicator-of-C"

\end_inset

 and Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prox_gamma_f_star_vee"

\end_inset

, we simplify the first two iterates of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-DRS"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\zeta_{n+1} & =\psi_{n}-\gamma\,\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\big(\gamma^{-1}\psi_{n}\big),\:\textrm{and}\\
\xi_{n+1} & =2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n}+\gamma\,\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\big(-\gamma^{-1}(2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n})\big).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these simplified iterates and introducing intermediate iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{y}_{n+1}=\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(\gamma^{-1}\psi_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{n+1}=\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\big(-\gamma^{-1}(2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n})\big)$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-DRS"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{y}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\big(\gamma^{-1}\psi_{n}\big)\\
\zeta_{n+1} & =\psi_{n}-\gamma\tilde{y}_{n+1}\\
\tilde{x}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\big(-\gamma^{-1}(2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n})\big)\\
 & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\big(-\gamma^{-1}(\psi_{n}-2\gamma\tilde{y}_{n+1})\big)\\
\xi_{n+1} & =2\zeta_{n+1}-\psi_{n}+\gamma\tilde{x}_{n+1}\\
 & =\psi_{n}-2\gamma\tilde{y}_{n+1}+\gamma\tilde{x}_{n+1}\\
\psi_{n+1} & =\psi_{n}+\xi_{n+1}-\zeta_{n+1}\\
 & =\psi_{n}-\gamma\tilde{y}_{n+1}+\gamma\tilde{x}_{n+1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{n}$
\end_inset

 do not have any explicit dependence, hence they can be removed.
 Furthermore, introduce a new iterate, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}=\frac{1}{\gamma}\psi_{n}-\tilde{x}_{n}$
\end_inset

 .
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}:=\gamma\left(z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 in the iteration scheme above, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{y}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}\right)\nonumber \\
\tilde{x}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\left(-\left(z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}-2\tilde{y}_{n+1}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & \overset{a)}{=}\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\left(-\left(z_{n+1}-\tilde{y}_{n+1}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}-\tilde{y}_{n+1},\label{eq:idw}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:idw"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we swap the order of of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the correct dependency:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{y}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}\right)\\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}+\tilde{x}_{n}-\tilde{y}_{n+1},\\
\tilde{x}_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\gamma^{-1}f}\left(\tilde{y}_{n+1}-z_{n+1}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We now substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{n}:=x_{n+1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{y}_{n}:=y_{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\gamma}:=\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 in the iterates above to obtain a relaxed version 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{n+1} & =\mathbf{prox}_{\tilde{\gamma}f}\left(y_{n}-z_{n}\right)\nonumber \\
y_{n+1} & =\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\left(z_{n}+x_{n+1}\right)\tag{Relaxed-NC-ADMM}\label{eq:ADMM-to-dual}\\
z_{n+1} & =z_{n}-y_{n+1}+x_{n+1},\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is similar to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, except the projection is onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 rather than onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constructing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we discuss how we can arrive at 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

.
 The first step requires the observation that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

 finds a minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that, construct the dual of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset

, which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{maximize} & -\left(f^{\star\vee}\right)^{\star\vee}\left(x\right)-\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}\left(x\right),\end{array}\tag{Double-Dual}\label{eq:double-dual}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the optimization variable.
 As both 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:double-dual"

\end_inset

 are convex optimization problems, strong duality usually holds (under constrain
t qualifications), where both problems have the same optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $-d^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(f^{\star\vee}\right)^{\star\vee}\overset{a)}{=}\left(f^{\vee\star}\right)^{\star\vee}\overset{}{=}\left(\left(f^{\vee}\right)^{\star\star}\right)^{\vee}\overset{b)}{=}f^{\vee\vee}\overset{c)}{=}f,$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a)$
\end_inset

 follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star\vee}=f^{\vee\star}$
\end_inset

 for CPC function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 13.20(v)"
key "Bauschke2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b)$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that the biconjugate of a CPC function is equal to
 the function itself 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Lemma 4.8"
key "beck2017first"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c)$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that applying reversal operation twice on a function
 returns the original function.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\mathcal{C}}^{\star\star}=\delta_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "biconjugate-of-indicator-of-C"

\end_inset

(i).
 Hence, the dual of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:double-dual"

\end_inset

, written as a minimization problem, is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & f\left(x\right)\\
\textup{subject to} & x\in\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C},
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the optimization variable with optimal value 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 So, under strong duality between 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:double-dual"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

 finds a minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, which appears in the projection step of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

.
 So, to solve the original problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 where we seek a minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

, an intuitive modification to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

 is replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 (hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

), which results in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

.
 Roughly speaking, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 is constructed by first relaxing the constraint set of the original problem
 to its convex hull, then applying the Douglas-Rachford splitting algorithm
 for the relaxed problem and finally restricting the resultant algorithm
 on the original constraint set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction procedure also provides an alternative explanation behind
 why, when compared with exact solvers, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 often achieves lower objective values in many numerical experiments performed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Diamond2018,Takapoui2017a,Takapoui2017,takapoui2016simple"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In these works, these lower objective values are attributed to the superior
 performance of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 in solving nonconvex problems based on empirical evidence.
 An alternative explanation could be that the heuristic is solving a modified
 dual problem, which, in the absence of strong duality, is guaranteed to
 yield an objective value that is smaller than or equal to that of the original
 problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Convergence-properties-of-NC-ADMM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we comment on convergence properties of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 in comparison with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet\,$
\end_inset


\series bold
Convergence to an optimal solution.

\series default
 Unlike 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 does not attack the original problem directly, hence it cannot characterize
 minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 in a similar manner.
 For 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

, the fixed point set of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}$
\end_inset

 acts as a bridge between global minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 and  the fixed point set of the nonconvex Douglas-Rachford operator (Theorem
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:minimizer_charecterization"

\end_inset

).
 Though 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:classic_DRS"

\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM-to-dual"

\end_inset

 under strong duality, no such equivalence exists between 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, because there is a strict duality gap between 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dual-opt"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}\neq\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

.
 This lack of equivalence prevents connecting the fixed point set of the
 underlying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 operator to global minimizers of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:original_problem"

\end_inset

 through the fixed point set of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\gamma\partial\delta_{\mathcal{C}}}R_{\gamma\partial f}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet\,$
\end_inset


\series bold
Convergence to a point.
 
\series default
Furthermore, the lack of equivalence between 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 makes it harder, if not impossible, to comment analogously on convergence
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 to a general point (not necessarily an optimal solution) as well.
 As shown in the proof of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset

, establishing convergence to a general point for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 depends on the interrelationship between the nonconvex Douglas-Rachford
 operator and the nonconvex Peaceman-Rachford operator.
 Unfortunately, such relationship breaks down for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

, because constructing such a relationship would require Moreau's decomposition
 to hold for nonconvex functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naturally, the next question to be considered is whether it is possible
 to characterize global minimizers and establish sufficient conditions for
 convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 without showing any equivalence between it and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

.
 However, there are strong indications that the answer is negative, which
 we discuss now.
 Our convergence analysis for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 is established for problems with nonempty, compact, but not necessarily
 convex constraint sets, but it is equally applicable to the smaller subclass
 of problems with convex constraint sets (recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Notes-on-NC-DRS_conv"

\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{\mathop{{\bf conv}}\mathcal{C}}=\mathbf{\tilde{\Pi}}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

, and both strong duality and Moreau's decomposition hold; these properties
 make 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 a special case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 in a convex setup, and one can establish convergence to an optimal solution
 from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(main-convergence-result)"

\end_inset

.
 However, when we move from a convex setup to a nonconvex one, these properties
 do not hold in general, and the operator-theoretic equivalence between
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 breaks down.
 So, it seems unlikely that for the class of problems that are not necessarily
 convex, one could characterize global minimizers and establish sufficient
 conditions for convergence of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ADMM_orig-1"

\end_inset

 completely ignoring 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DR_splitting_orig"

\end_inset

, because the algorithms are equivalent to each other for the subclass of
 convex problems, where the equivalence is dependent on properties that
 are exclusive to a convex setup.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discussion in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
S
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Main-convergence-result"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

